data.content:
## C# 14 Span Overload Resolution Change

In C# 14, new built-in span conversions cause `array.Contains(num)` to bind to **`MemoryExtensions.Contains(ReadOnlySpan<T>, T)`** instead of `Enumerable.Contains<T>(IEnumerable<T>, T)`. Expression trees cannot represent span-based method calls, so this throws at runtime.

### Fix

Force the `Enumerable.Contains` overload by casting to `IEnumerable<int>`:

```csharp
// Option 1: Cast to IEnumerable<int>
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => ((IEnumerable<int>)array).Contains(num);

// Option 2: Use Enumerable.Contains explicitly
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => Enumerable.Contains(array, num);
```

The same issue affects **`Reverse()`** on arrays (now resolves to the in-place `Span` extension returning `void` instead of `Enumerable.Reverse`). Apply the same pattern: use `.AsEnumerable()` or call `Enumerable.Reverse(arr)` explicitly.
